Title: The Power Principle and Tail-Fatness Uncertainty
Author-Name: Roger Gay
Author-X-Name-First: Roger
Author-X-Name-Last: Gay
Author-Email: Roger.Gay@buseco.monash.edu.au
Keywords: Exponential principle, power principle, constant risk aversion, ratio premium, stop-loss insurance
Abstract: When insurance claims are governed by fat-tailed distributions, gross uncertainty about the value of the tail-fatness index is virtually inescapable.  In this paper a new premium principle (the power principle) analogous to the exponential principle for thin-tailed claims, is discussed.  Pareto premiums determined under the principle have a transparent ratio structure, cater convincingly for uncertainty in the tail-fatness index, and are applicable in passage to the extremal limit, to all fat-tailed distributions in the domain of attraction of the (Frechet) extreme-value distribution. Cover can be provided for part claims if existence of the claims mean is in doubt. Stop-loss premiums are also discussed.  Mathematical requirements are very modest.
